7.3.2 - Day 2 → 21/03/2026 → Game Engine Folder Architecture
Today’s focus was on establishing a scalable, high‑performance folder structure for the Game Engine project. The architecture now cleanly separates the Application, Editor, and Engine layers while also introducing shared systems, third‑party dependencies, and tooling support. The structure is designed to support C++, C#, and Python workflows without creating cross‑contamination between runtime, editor, and core engine code.
Completed / What Is Done & What Could Be Improved
Completed
Designed a full top‑level folder layout:
Application (runtime + exported builds)
Editor (creation tools, UI, asset pipeline)
Engine (renderer, physics, ECS, platform layer)
Shared, ThirdParty, Tools, Scripts
Broke each major folder into logical submodules:
Rendering backends (Vulkan, DX12, Metal, OpenGL)
ECS, scene systems, animation, audio, networking
Editor panels, inspectors, serialization, asset importers
Application‑side assets, builds, configs
Ensured the structure mirrors industry‑proven patterns (Unreal, Godot, Unity, custom AAA engines)
Organized scripting bindings for C# and Python in a clean, centralized location
What Could Be Improved
The Engine/Platform layer could be expanded with more granular OS‑specific abstractions.
The Editor/Tools section may eventually need a plugin system folder for modular extensions.
The Application/Runtime folder might benefit from a clearer separation between gameplay logic and UI frameworks.
Build system integration (CMake, Premake, or custom) still needs to be mapped to this structure.
Next Steps
Define a module dependency graph to prevent circular references between Engine, Editor, and Application.
Establish naming conventions and namespace rules for C++, C#, and Python code.
Begin drafting the CMake or build pipeline that aligns with this folder structure.
Create a minimal “Hello Engine” bootstrap inside /Engine/Core to validate the architecture.
Set up the Editor launcher and basic windowing under /Editor/UI and /Engine/Platform.
This structure sets the foundation for a clean, scalable, and professional‑grade game engine. With the architecture now solidified, the next phase is all about wiring systems together and validating the flow between Engine → Editor → Application. The groundwork is strong — now it’s time to bring it to life.

